@node Sorting without filling
@section Sorting without filling

@findex org-ref-sort-bibtex-entry
The command @code{org-ref-sort-bibtex-entry} reorders the fields within a Bib@TeX{} entry according to the precedence defined in @code{org-ref-bibtex-sort-order}. In the upstream version, after sorting the fields the command calls @code{bibtex-fill-entry}, which reformats every field value by wrapping long lines to fit within a fixed column width. This automatic filling can be undesirable when you want to preserve the exact formatting of field values, especially for entries with long URLs or titles that are more readable on a single line.

The @samp{el-patch} in @samp{org-ref-extras.el} removes the @code{bibtex-fill-entry} call while keeping the rest of the sorting and cleaning logic intact. The entry is still cleaned by @code{bibtex-clean-entry} after sorting, which validates the entry structure without altering line breaks within field values.

@node ISBN import cleanup
@section ISBN import cleanup

@findex isbn-to-bibtex
The command @code{isbn-to-bibtex} (from @samp{org-ref-isbn}) fetches a Bib@TeX{} entry for a given ISBN from the @samp{www.ebook.de} service and inserts it into a bibliography file. The fetched data frequently includes a @samp{Year} field alongside a @samp{date} field, creating redundancy that can confuse Bib@TeX{} processors or produce duplicate information in formatted citations.

The @samp{el-patch} in @samp{org-ref-extras.el} adds a post-processing step that removes any line matching @samp{Year =...} from the fetched entry string before it is inserted into the bibliography and cleaned. This ensures that only the @samp{date} field (which is the preferred field in modern Bib@LaTeX{} usage) survives the import process. The rest of the import workflow --- including ISBN prompting from the region or kill ring, entry cleaning via @code{org-ref-isbn-clean-bibtex-entry} and @code{org-ref-clean-bibtex-entry}, and saving the file --- remains unchanged.

